1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,195
When we think about working with numbers and for loops,

2

00:00:04,195  -->  00:00:08,360
let's run an example where we can see exactly how to use

3

00:00:08,360  -->  00:00:12,700
a for loop to iterate over a sequence of numbers using the range function.

4

00:00:12,700  -->  00:00:15,640
We'll be going through the range function in an upcoming section,

5

00:00:15,640  -->  00:00:17,920
so don't worry about memorizing it right now.

6

00:00:17,920  -->  00:00:20,380
But let's look at why a for loop is

7

00:00:20,380  -->  00:00:24,220
the best choice when iterating through a range of numbers.

8

00:00:24,220  -->  00:00:26,730
We'll declare our for loop like this,

9

00:00:26,730  -->  00:00:32,850
and we'll say for i in range 5,

10

00:00:32,850  -->  00:00:35,925
and then we'll print i.

11

00:00:35,925  -->  00:00:39,975
This code outputs the numbers from 0-4,

12

00:00:39,975  -->  00:00:44,350
the numbers between 0-5 denoted with this range function.

13

00:00:44,350  -->  00:00:47,430
Using a for loop here is more optimal than

14

00:00:47,430  -->  00:00:50,310
a while loop for iterating through a range of numbers,

15

00:00:50,310  -->  00:00:52,625
because once we execute this code,

16

00:00:52,625  -->  00:00:56,150
we're able to get all of those numbers very easily and

17

00:00:56,150  -->  00:01:00,910
cleanly using this range function to count up to five.

18

00:01:04,100  -->  00:01:08,470
Now, let's see how for loops work with strings.

19

00:01:08,470  -->  00:01:14,210
In this example, we're going to be iterating over each character in the word Python.

20

00:01:14,210  -->  00:01:17,490
This allows us to handle each character individually within

21

00:01:17,490  -->  00:01:21,415
a loop through the for loop construction.

22

00:01:21,415  -->  00:01:24,370
For loops can iterate over each character in a string,

23

00:01:24,370  -->  00:01:30,130
allowing us to count our way through a list of characters. Let's see how to do that.

24

00:01:30,130  -->  00:01:36,890
We'll first declare a variable called word and we'll set that equal to a string,

25

00:01:36,890  -->  00:01:40,010
which we put the Python word in for.

26

00:01:40,010  -->  00:01:44,080
Then we'll say for letter in word,

27

00:01:44,080  -->  00:01:47,715
and then we'll print letter.

28

00:01:47,715  -->  00:01:50,975
What we're doing is we're saying for

29

00:01:50,975  -->  00:01:58,825
the incrementable item in word print, what its value is.

30

00:01:58,825  -->  00:02:01,850
Can you guess what the output will be here?

31

00:02:05,440  -->  00:02:09,450
This will output each letter in the word Python like this.

32

00:02:09,450  -->  00:02:11,730
And if you guessed that, you're right.

33

00:02:11,730  -->  00:02:15,615
Great job. Next,

34

00:02:15,615  -->  00:02:18,660
let's see how for loops work with lists.

35

00:02:18,660  -->  00:02:21,520
A list in Python is another way to say array,

36

00:02:21,520  -->  00:02:26,920
which is a fancy word for saying a collection of things put inside of square brackets.

37

00:02:26,920  -->  00:02:33,435
If we had a list of fruits in an array defined by brackets,

38

00:02:33,435  -->  00:02:36,040
we could use a for loop to iterate over

39

00:02:36,040  -->  00:02:40,020
each fruit to tell us which fruits are in that list.

40

00:02:40,020  -->  00:02:42,760
Let's see an example of how to do this.

41

00:02:42,760  -->  00:02:45,120
So first, we will create a list,

42

00:02:45,120  -->  00:02:51,200
which would be a variable set equal to square brackets,

43

00:02:51,200  -->  00:02:52,880
and then a list of items,

44

00:02:52,880  -->  00:02:54,620
which we'll put as strings here.

45

00:02:54,620  -->  00:02:58,040
So apple, banana, cherry, and grape fruit.

46

00:02:58,820  -->  00:03:05,050
Next, we'll write a for loop to iterate over each of these items in the list.

47

00:03:05,050  -->  00:03:10,120
We'll say for fruit in fruits,

48

00:03:10,120  -->  00:03:14,595
and then we'll print each fruit item.

49

00:03:14,595  -->  00:03:18,590
What we're doing is we're saying for each item,

50

00:03:18,590  -->  00:03:20,600
and we could call this really anything.

51

00:03:20,600  -->  00:03:22,350
We could call it i, we could call it item,

52

00:03:22,350  -->  00:03:24,370
we could call it shopping cart item,

53

00:03:24,370  -->  00:03:27,770
but we're going to call it fruit in fruits,

54

00:03:27,770  -->  00:03:29,810
which is the array we set above here,

55

00:03:29,810  -->  00:03:36,090
and then we're going to print each of those items in the list that it finds.

56

00:03:36,090  -->  00:03:39,330
Can you guess what the output will be here?

57

00:03:43,130  -->  00:03:45,730
We get apple, banana, cherry,

58

00:03:45,730  -->  00:03:48,655
and grape fruit in the same order that is defined in the list.

59

00:03:48,655  -->  00:03:51,850
If you said this, you're right. Great job.

60

00:03:52,730  -->  00:03:57,750
Next up, let's see how for loops work with tuples.

61

00:03:57,750  -->  00:04:01,630
A tuple is similar to a list like what we just saw earlier,

62

00:04:01,630  -->  00:04:04,750
but data can easily be changeable.

63

00:04:04,750  -->  00:04:07,930
We could have two fruits or 20 fruits,

64

00:04:07,930  -->  00:04:10,870
depending on what you put in your shopping cart, for example.

65

00:04:10,870  -->  00:04:14,610
But what if we had data that couldn't or shouldn't ever change?

66

00:04:14,610  -->  00:04:16,930
We call that type of data immutable,

67

00:04:16,930  -->  00:04:20,810
which is a fancy word for saying the data cannot be changed, edited,

68

00:04:20,810  -->  00:04:23,270
or deleted after it's created,

69

00:04:23,270  -->  00:04:25,990
and is organized in parentheses,

70

00:04:25,990  -->  00:04:28,570
not brackets, like a list.

71

00:04:28,570  -->  00:04:33,900
That being said, we can still iterate over a tuple in the same way as a list above.

72

00:04:33,900  -->  00:04:37,320
Let's see how we can iterate over a tuple.

73

00:04:37,320  -->  00:04:45,780
We'll set our coordinates variable equal to a tuple of coordinates.

74

00:04:45,780  -->  00:04:48,555
We'll say 43, say 62,

75

00:04:48,555  -->  00:04:51,100
and we'll say 89.

76

00:04:51,470  -->  00:04:57,840
Then we'll write our for loop and we'll say for coordinate in

77

00:04:57,840  -->  00:05:06,910
coordinates, we'll print coordinate.

78

00:05:09,170  -->  00:05:15,570
What we're doing here is that we're setting an immutable set of data,

79

00:05:15,570  -->  00:05:17,370
which we're calling a tuple here,

80

00:05:17,370  -->  00:05:19,710
and then we're going to iterate over

81

00:05:19,710  -->  00:05:25,590
each item in our coordinate tuple, and print that out here.

82

00:05:25,590  -->  00:05:28,430
Can you guess what the output will be?

83

00:05:30,990  -->  00:05:37,110
Here, we'll see an output of each coordinate in the tuple: 43,

84

00:05:37,110  -->  00:05:39,390
right here, 62 right there,

85

00:05:39,390  -->  00:05:41,750
and 89 right there.

86

00:05:42,350  -->  00:05:46,800
Now, let's see how for loops work with sets.

87

00:05:46,800  -->  00:05:50,960
A set is a collection of unique items organized with curly brackets,

88

00:05:50,960  -->  00:05:54,020
and have some unique properties that make them very different

89

00:05:54,020  -->  00:05:57,520
from the other data structures we've mentioned previously.

90

00:05:57,520  -->  00:06:01,460
Sets are unordered, meaning the items do not have a defined order,

91

00:06:01,460  -->  00:06:04,520
and their sequence may vary each time you use them.

92

00:06:04,520  -->  00:06:10,200
They're also unindexed, so you cannot access items by their position in a set.

93

00:06:10,200  -->  00:06:12,360
They are also mutable,

94

00:06:12,360  -->  00:06:14,980
allowing you to add and remove items.

95

00:06:14,980  -->  00:06:17,580
Although once an item is added to that set,

96

00:06:17,580  -->  00:06:19,855
its value cannot be changed.

97

00:06:19,855  -->  00:06:23,080
Finally, they only contain unique items,

98

00:06:23,080  -->  00:06:26,540
meaning any duplicate values will be ignored.

99

00:06:26,540  -->  00:06:29,400
Here's how we can iterate over a set.

100

00:06:29,400  -->  00:06:37,530
What we'll do is that we will write a set like this and we'll say unique_fruits equal.

101

00:06:37,530  -->  00:06:39,420
We'll put curly bracket here,

102

00:06:39,420  -->  00:06:45,220
and then we'll put in a list of fruits like this.

103

00:06:45,470  -->  00:06:47,835
Then in our for loop,

104

00:06:47,835  -->  00:06:54,090
we'll say for fruit in unique_fruits right here,

105

00:06:54,090  -->  00:06:59,425
put a colon and then we'll print fruit.

106

00:06:59,425  -->  00:07:03,180
This will output each unique fruit in the set.

107

00:07:03,180  -->  00:07:07,460
Can you guess what the output of this will be once we execute it?

108

00:07:11,480  -->  00:07:14,805
We see cherry, banana, and apple.

109

00:07:14,805  -->  00:07:16,650
If you said that, you're right.

110

00:07:16,650  -->  00:07:19,450
This will output each unique fruit in the set,

111

00:07:19,450  -->  00:07:22,750
but notice how apple is only printed once,

112

00:07:22,750  -->  00:07:25,370
as it's right there and right there,

113

00:07:25,370  -->  00:07:27,750
but it's only printed out once there,

114

00:07:27,750  -->  00:07:29,070
because it is a duplicate,

115

00:07:29,070  -->  00:07:32,250
and we will only see unique items in a set,

116

00:07:32,250  -->  00:07:36,070
and that's why we only see these items here.

117

00:07:36,980  -->  00:07:40,750
As we continue to work with for loops and sets,

118

00:07:40,750  -->  00:07:44,370
let's see another example of how we could use a for loop to check

119

00:07:44,370  -->  00:07:48,840
a membership allow list for multiple items against a set.

120

00:07:48,840  -->  00:07:52,225
Let's see how to do that. First,

121

00:07:52,225  -->  00:07:56,370
we'll create a set and declare that as the allowed users.

122

00:07:56,370  -->  00:08:00,000
And in this set, we have Alice, Bob, and Charlie.

123

00:08:00,000  -->  00:08:03,885
Next, we'll create a list of users_to_check,

124

00:08:03,885  -->  00:08:06,360
and we'll define this as a list,

125

00:08:06,360  -->  00:08:08,750
an array called users_to_check,

126

00:08:08,750  -->  00:08:10,090
and that has David,

127

00:08:10,090  -->  00:08:13,090
Alice, Eve, and Bob.

128

00:08:13,790  -->  00:08:19,130
Then we'll write our for loop to check over each user.

129

00:08:19,130  -->  00:08:25,150
We'll write for user in users_to_check with a colon,

130

00:08:25,150  -->  00:08:33,360
and then we'll say if user in allowed_users will print an f statement,

131

00:08:33,740  -->  00:08:35,880
An f string here,

132

00:08:35,880  -->  00:08:40,960
and we'll say user is allowed.

133

00:08:40,960  -->  00:08:43,295
We'll close out that print statement.

134

00:08:43,295  -->  00:08:45,965
Then we'll say else,

135

00:08:45,965  -->  00:08:49,250
and then we'll print the else statement,

136

00:08:49,250  -->  00:08:51,180
and we'll do another f string,

137

00:08:51,180  -->  00:08:59,395
and we'll say user is not allowed, then we'll close that up.

138

00:08:59,395  -->  00:09:07,980
In this example, the for loop iterates over each user in the users_to_check list.

139

00:09:07,980  -->  00:09:14,630
Then checks if that user is in the allowed_users variable,

140

00:09:14,630  -->  00:09:16,590
which we've declared as a set,

141

00:09:16,590  -->  00:09:18,950
which is happening right here.

142

00:09:18,950  -->  00:09:21,330
The result is printed accordingly.

143

00:09:21,330  -->  00:09:24,190
This approach leverages the efficiency of sets for

144

00:09:24,190  -->  00:09:28,430
membership testing within a loop that processes multiple items.

145

00:09:28,430  -->  00:09:31,890
Can you guess what the output is going to be here?

146

00:09:31,950  -->  00:09:35,390
Let's run this code and find out.

147

00:09:36,660  -->  00:09:41,335
After running the cell, we see David is not allowed,

148

00:09:41,335  -->  00:09:43,980
Alice is allowed, Eve is not allowed,

149

00:09:43,980  -->  00:09:45,415
and Bob is allowed.

150

00:09:45,415  -->  00:09:49,155
We can see this because in the users_to_check,

151

00:09:49,155  -->  00:09:52,495
David does not appear in the allowed list of users.

152

00:09:52,495  -->  00:09:55,440
However, Alice is in that list.

153

00:09:55,440  -->  00:09:59,640
Eve does not appear in the set of allowed users,

154

00:09:59,640  -->  00:10:02,260
but Bob is. Bob is there.

155

00:10:02,260  -->  00:10:05,600
We do see that Charlie is one of the allowed users,

156

00:10:05,600  -->  00:10:10,025
but does not show up in the users_to_check list.

157

00:10:10,025  -->  00:10:15,145
Did you notice that only two users are allowed in this user check as well?

158

00:10:15,145  -->  00:10:20,300
Again, this is because Charlie did not come up in the users_to_check list,

159

00:10:20,300  -->  00:10:23,010
so we wouldn't have iterated over Charlie

160

00:10:23,010  -->  00:10:26,305
when we were checking our user and users_to_check.

161

00:10:26,305  -->  00:10:29,890
As you can see, for loops are very versatile, powerful,

162

00:10:29,890  -->  00:10:32,530
and can be used to iterate over many different types

163

00:10:32,530  -->  00:10:36,070
of varied sequences and collections in Python.

164

00:10:36,070  -->  00:10:41,870
For loops can also iterate over the keys and values of a dictionary.

165

00:10:41,870  -->  00:10:45,210
Think of a dictionary as a real dictionary book that

166

00:10:45,210  -->  00:10:49,190
stores a giant alphabetical list of words and their definitions.

167

00:10:49,190  -->  00:10:54,090
Similarly, a Python dictionary stores data objects as key value pairs.

168

00:10:54,090  -->  00:10:58,150
In this case, we are defining a data object called person

169

00:10:58,150  -->  00:11:02,890
with three values: Name, age, and city.

170

00:11:02,890  -->  00:11:05,540
The name has a string value, age,

171

00:11:05,540  -->  00:11:08,700
an integer value, and city, a string value.

172

00:11:08,700  -->  00:11:11,320
These key value pairs have a key,

173

00:11:11,320  -->  00:11:13,940
the first part, and a value, the second part,

174

00:11:13,940  -->  00:11:18,280
separated by a colon with the key representing an identifier,

175

00:11:18,280  -->  00:11:21,380
and the value representing the corresponding data,

176

00:11:21,380  -->  00:11:23,220
which can be of any data type,

177

00:11:23,220  -->  00:11:25,740
such as a string or an integer.

178

00:11:25,740  -->  00:11:32,815
Let's see how we can work with these key value pairs of a dictionary with a for loop.

179

00:11:32,815  -->  00:11:39,300
To do this, we'll define our person object like this.

180

00:11:39,300  -->  00:11:43,060
So we'll use squiggly brackets like this,

181

00:11:43,060  -->  00:11:45,580
and you'll see name set to Alice,

182

00:11:45,580  -->  00:11:47,080
age is 25,

183

00:11:47,080  -->  00:11:49,895
and City as New York.

184

00:11:49,895  -->  00:11:53,780
We can also write this a little bit more cleanly to see,

185

00:11:53,780  -->  00:11:56,500
and this is something that I will usually do,

186

00:11:56,500  -->  00:12:00,500
where I'll put each item on a new line so you can clearly see

187

00:12:00,500  -->  00:12:04,965
which items are the key value pairs of a dictionary.

188

00:12:04,965  -->  00:12:14,800
Then we'll write our for loop and we'll say for key value in person.items,

189

00:12:14,800  -->  00:12:18,240
because there's multiple items in person.

190

00:12:18,240  -->  00:12:21,050
Do a colon, and we'll say print,

191

00:12:21,050  -->  00:12:23,045
and we'll do another f string,

192

00:12:23,045  -->  00:12:28,990
and we'll say key, colon, value.

193

00:12:29,450  -->  00:12:33,795
Then we'll close that out with the double quotes,

194

00:12:33,795  -->  00:12:38,140
and then we'll close that out with our parenthese.

195

00:12:40,010  -->  00:12:44,420
This should output each key value pair in the dictionary.

196

00:12:44,420  -->  00:12:49,790
Can you guess what the output is going to look like when we execute the cell?

197

00:12:49,840  -->  00:12:52,980
Let's find out what it'll print.

198

00:12:55,730  -->  00:12:59,570
Here we see name is Alice,

199

00:12:59,570  -->  00:13:02,770
age is 25, and City is New York,

200

00:13:02,770  -->  00:13:05,680
exactly as we defined it in the dictionary.

201

00:13:05,680  -->  00:13:08,330
As you can see, for loops allow you to easily

202

00:13:08,330  -->  00:13:11,270
iterate over the keys and values in a dictionary,

203

00:13:11,270  -->  00:13:16,190
making it a powerful tool for working with structured data like this.
